# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-von-schoeler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The entirety of Germany was occupied and administered by the Allies of World War II, from the Berlin Declaration on 5 June 1945 to the establishment of West Germany on 23 May 1949.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Nazi Germany was stripped of its sovereignty and its government was entirely dissolved.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] After Germany formally surrendered on Tuesday, 8 May 1945, the four countries representing the Allies (the United States, United Kingdom, Soviet Union, and France) asserted joint authority and sovereignty through the Allied Control Council (ACC).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Germany after the war was a devastated country – roughly 80 percent of its infrastructure was in need of repair or reconstruction – which helped the idea that Germany was entering a new phase of history ("zero hour").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] At first, Allied-occupied Germany was defined as all territories of Germany before the 1938 Nazi annexation of Austria.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] All territories annexed by Germany before the war from Austria and Czechoslovakia were returned to these countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Memel Territory, annexed by Germany from Lithuania before the war, was annexed by the Soviet Union in 1945 and transferred to the Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] All territories annexed by Germany during the war from Belgium, France, Italy, Luxembourg, Poland, the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia were returned to their respective countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] This treaty was expected to confirm the shifting westward of Poland's borders, as the United Kingdom and United States committed themselves to support the permanent incorporation of eastern Germany into Poland and the Soviet Union.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In the closing weeks of fighting in Europe, United States forces had pushed beyond the agreed boundaries for the future zones of occupation, in some places by as much as 320 km (200 miles).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The so-called line of contact between Soviet and U.S. forces at the end of hostilities, mostly lying eastward of the July 1945-established inner German border, was temporary.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] After two months during which they held areas that had been assigned to the Soviet zone, U.S. forces withdrew in the first days of July 1945.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Some have concluded that this was a crucial move which persuaded the Soviet Union to allow American, British and French forces into their designated sectors in Berlin, which occurred at roughly the same time; the need for intelligence gathering (Operation Paperclip) may also have been a factor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] After the Soviet withdrawal from the Allied Control Council on 20 March 1948, the split had led to the 1949 establishment of two new German states, the Federal Republic of Germany (FRG, West Germany) and the German Democratic Republic (GDR, East Germany).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Those formed Württemberg-Baden and became northern portions of the present-day German state of Baden-Württemberg founded in 1952.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The ports of Bremen (on the lower Weser River) and Bremerhaven (at the Weser estuary of the North Sea) were also placed under U.S. control because of the U.S. request to have certain toeholds in Northern Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The headquarters of the American military government was the former IG Farben Building in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] By May 1945 the British and Canadian Armies had liberated the Netherlands and had conquered Northern Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Canadian forces went home following the German surrender, leaving Northern Germany to be occupied by the British.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The British Army of the Rhine was formed on 25 August 1945 from the British Liberation Army.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In July the British withdrew from Mecklenburg's capital Schwerin which they had taken over from the Americans a few weeks before, as it had previously been agreed to be occupied by the Soviet Army.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Within the British zone of occupation, the CCG/BE re-established the city of Hamburg as a German state, but with borders that had been drawn by the Nazi government in 1937.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Also in 1947, the American zone of occupation being inland had no port facilities – thus the Free Hanseatic City of Bremen and Bremerhaven became exclaves within the British zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The British headquarters were originally based in Bad Oeynhausen from 1946, but in 1954 it was moved to Mönchengladbach where it was known as JHQ Rheindahlen.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Another special feature of the British zone was the enclave of Bonn.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] It was created in July 1949 and was not under British or any other allied control.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Instead it was under the control of the Allied High Commission.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In June 1950, Ivone Kirkpatrick became the British High Commissioner for Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Kirkpatrick carried immense responsibility particularly with respect to the negotiation of the Bonn–Paris conventions during 1951–1952, which terminated the occupation and prepared the way for the rearmament of West Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] , formerly the Stadt Hamburg Hotel in late 1945.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] British armored car, at the Brandenburg Gate in Berlin, 1950.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Army units from other countries were stationed within the British occupation zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The French Republic was at first not granted an occupation zone in Germany, but the British and American governments later agreed to cede some western parts of their zones of occupation to the French Army.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In April and May 1945, the French 1st Army had captured Karlsruhe and Stuttgart, and conquered a territory extending to Hitler's Eagle's Nest and the westernmost part of Austria.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In July, the French relinquished Stuttgart to the Americans, and in exchange were given control over cities west of the Rhine such as Mainz and Koblenz.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] All this resulted in two barely contiguous areas of Germany along the French border which met at just a single point along the River Rhine.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Three German states (*Land*) were established: Rheinland Pfalz in the north and west and on the other hand Württemberg-Hohenzollern and South Baden, who later formed Baden-Württemberg together with Württemberg-Baden of the American zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The French zone of occupation included the Saargebiet, which was disentangled from it on 16 February 1946.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] By 18 December 1946 customs controls were established between the Saar area and Allied-occupied Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The French zone ceded further areas adjacent to the Saar (in mid-1946, early 1947, and early 1949).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Included in the French zone was the town of Büsingen am Hochrhein, a German exclave separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of neutral Swiss territory.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Swiss government agreed to allow limited numbers of French troops to pass through its territory in order to maintain law and order in Büsingen.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] From November 1945, Luxembourg was allocated a zone within the French sector.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Luxembourg 2nd Infantry Battalion was garrisoned in Bitburg and the 1st Battalion was sent to Saarburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The final Luxembourg forces in Germany, in Bitburg, left in 1955.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Soviet occupation zone incorporated Thuringia, Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, Brandenburg and Mecklenburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Soviet Military Administration was headquartered in Berlin-Karlshorst, which also came to house the chief *rezidentura* of Soviet intelligence in Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] While located wholly within the Soviet zone, because of its symbolic importance as the nation's capital and seat of the former Nazi government, the city of Berlin was jointly occupied by the Allied powers and subdivided into four sectors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] All four occupying powers were entitled to privileges throughout Berlin that were not extended to the rest of Germany – this included the Soviet sector of Berlin, which was legally separate from the rest of the Soviet zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] A small area west of the Oder, near Szczecin, also fell to Poland.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Most German citizens residing in these areas were subsequently expropriated and expelled.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Returning refugees, who had fled from war hostilities, were denied return.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Saarland, an area in the French occupation zone, was separated from Allied-occupied Germany to become a French protectorate with its constitution took effect on 17 December 1947, however the separation was opposed by the Soviet Union and Germans here were not expelled.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Another dispute was the absorption of post-war expellees.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Therefore, France strictly refused to absorb war refugees who were denied return to their homes in seized eastern German territories or destitute post-war expellees who had been expropriated there, into the French zone, let alone into the separated Saar protectorate.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] However, the native population, returning after Nazi-imposed removals (e.g., political and Jewish refugees) and war-related relocations (e.g., evacuation from air raids), were allowed to return home in the areas under French control.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The other Allies complained that they had to shoulder the burden to feed, house and clothe the expellees who had to leave their belongings behind.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In practice, each of the four occupying powers wielded government authority in their respective zones and carried out different policies toward the population and local and state governments there.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] A uniform administration of the western zones evolved, known first as the Bizone (the American and British zones merged as of 1 January 1947) and later the Trizone (after inclusion of the French zone).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The complete breakdown of east–west allied cooperation and joint administration in Germany became clear with the Soviet imposition of the Berlin Blockade that was enforced from June 1948 to May 1949.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The three western zones were merged to form the Federal Republic of Germany (FRG) i.e.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] West Germany in May 1949, and after that the Soviets followed suit in October 1949 with the establishment of the German Democratic Republic (GDR) i.e.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In the west, the occupation continued until 5 May 1955, when the General Treaty (German: *Deutschlandvertrag*) entered into force.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] However, upon the creation of the Federal Republic in May 1949, the military governors were replaced by civilian high commissioners, whose powers lay somewhere between those of a governor and those of an ambassador.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] When the *Deutschlandvertrag* became law, the occupation ended, the western occupation zones ceased to exist, and the high commissioners were replaced by normal ambassadors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] West Germany was also allowed to build a military, and the Bundeswehr, or Federal Defense Force, was established on 12 November 1955.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] A similar situation occurred in East Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] On 10 October the Soviet Military Administration in Germany was replaced by the Soviet Control Commission, although limited sovereignty was not granted to the GDR government until 11 November 1949.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] After the death of Joseph Stalin in March 1953, the Soviet Control Commission was replaced with the office of the Soviet High Commissioner on 28 May 1953.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] This office was abolished (and replaced by an ambassador) and (general) sovereignty was granted to the GDR, when the Soviet Union concluded a state treaty *(Staatsvertrag)* with the GDR on 20 September 1955.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] On 1 March 1956, the GDR established a military, the National People's Army (NVA).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Despite the grants of general sovereignty to both German states in 1955, full and unrestricted sovereignty under international law was not enjoyed by any German government until after the reunification of Germany in October 1990.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Though West Germany was effectively independent, the western Allies maintained limited legal jurisdiction over 'Germany as a whole' in respect of West Germany and Berlin.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] At the same time, East Germany progressed from being a satellite state of the Soviet Union to increasing independence of action; while still deferring in matters of security to Soviet authority.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The provisions of the Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany, also known as the "Two-plus-Four Treaty", granting full sovereign powers to Germany did not become law until 15 March 1991, after all of the participating governments had ratified the treaty.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] As envisaged by the Treaty, the last occupation troops departed from Germany when the Russian presence was terminated in 1994, although the Belgian Forces in Germany stayed in German territory until the end of 2005.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] A 1956 plebiscite ended the French administration of the Saar protectorate, and it joined the Federal Republic as *Saarland* on 1 January 1957, becoming its tenth state.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The city of Berlin was not part of either state and de jure continued to be under Allied occupation of the four countries until the reunification of Germany in October 1990.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] For administrative purposes, the three western sectors of Berlin were merged into the entity of West Berlin being de facto part of the FRG.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Soviet sector became known as East Berlin and while not recognised by the Western powers as a part of East Germany, the GDR declared it its capital (Hauptstadt der DDR).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The consensus among the Allies was that it was necessary to ensure Germany could not cause further world wars, but beyond that their opinion on what Germany's future should look like differed.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The US originally considered a punitive approach championed by Roosevelt's Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Morgenthau Jr.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Under this plan, Germany would have been broken into four autonomous states and not only demilitarized but also deindustrialized to the point of becoming chiefly agrarian.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Morgenthau Plan was opposed by Secretary of State Cordell Hull and War Secretary Henry L.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Stimson, and Roosevelt distanced himself from the idea after it was reported on by major American newspapers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Ultimately, US occupation policy came to be determined chiefly by the War Department, with long-term objectives summed up by the four Ds: *denazification, democratization, demilitarization, and decentralization (or decartelization)*.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Initially, the US was extremely rigorous in its efforts to prevent fraternization with German civilians.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] US soldiers were forbidden to shake hands with Germans, visit their homes, play games or sports with them, exchange gifts, take part in social events, or walk in the streets with them.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] How strictly this policy was applied varied from place to place, but in many places the restrictions were frequently ignored, as a result of which the policy was quickly abandoned.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Germans were also prohibited from inhabiting any part of a building in which US soldiers were housed, leading to large numbers of Germans being ejected from their homes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Denazification in the American zone included the complete closure of all Nazi German media, after which the US military government began granting licenses to Germans who had not been involved in Nazi propaganda to establish new publications.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Newspapers established via this process included *Frankfurter Rundschau* (August 1945), *Der Tagesspiegel* (Berlin, September 1945), and *Süddeutsche Zeitung* (Munich, October 1945).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Radio stations were initially operated only by the American Forces Network, whose stations included AFN Munich, AFN Frankfurt, and AFN Stuttgart.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In 1946, *Rundfunk im amerikanischen Sektor* (RIAS), which was supervised by the military government's Information Control Division, began to broadcast from Berlin.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Later, these stations were joined by the German-operated *Hessischer Rundfunk*, *Bayerischer Rundfunk*, and *Süddeutscher Rundfunk*.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] British occupation policy was similar to that of the United States, but with a greater focus on economic problems.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The British occupation zone included the Ruhr industrial region, which had experienced the heaviest bombing and therefore faced the greatest shortages of housing and food.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Initial British occupation directives were concerned primarily with economic considerations and food supply.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] To further the long-term aim of democratization, the British implemented government modeled on the UK system, placing heavy emphasis on local level democracy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The goal was to create a British-style administration with employees who viewed themselves as public servants, on the basis that this would help to reeducate Germans to democratic modes of thought.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] To that end the British introduced new local government structures, including a nonpolitical position similar to the English town clerk ("city director") that replaced the office of mayor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In general, the British believed strongly in reeducation as a means to achieve democracy, which led them to prioritize the reestablishment of schooling and university education in their zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The French were less concerned with improving Germany's moral and civic character, focusing instead on ensuring France's future security and utilizing the resources of their occupation zone to facilitate economic recovery within France itself.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Since one of their key goals was to ensure that Germany would never again be in a position to threaten France, the French were strongly opposed to a unified approach to occupation, and favored political structures that were as decentralized as possible.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] On the economic front, the French seized the opportunity to extract coal and steel resources from the Saar region, fusing it with France in a customs and currency union and encouraging the development of export industries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] As a result, the French managed to extract a surplus from their occupation zone, and prevented it from becoming a financial liability the way the British and American zones were to their respective occupying powers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Soviet aims in Germany were similar to those of the French, with the primary goals being to prevent future aggression by Germany and to extract reparations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Political activity in the Soviet occupation zone was overseen by the Soviet Military Administration (SMAD), which maintained close control over the Germans and allowed little room for independent action on the part of local German officials.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Key posts in local administration, particularly those dealing with security members, were given to members of the Communist party.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Soviet occupation authorities also executed a rigorous program of land reform, expropriating large landed estates and imposing direct control over much of the economic activity in the zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] They closed major banks and insurance companies in July 1945, and seized property formerly belonging to the German state, Wehrmacht, Nazi party, and Nazi organizations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The Soviets used suspicion of supposed Werwolf activity to tighten police control and secure forced labor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The food situation in occupied Germany was initially very dire.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] By the spring of 1946 the official ration in the American zone was no more than 1,275 calories (5,330 kJ) per day, with some areas probably receiving as little as 700 calories (2,900 kJ) per day.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In the British zone the food situation was dire, as found during a visit by the British (and Jewish) publisher Victor Gollancz in October and November 1946.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In Düsseldorf the normal 28-day allocation should have been 1,548 calories (6,480 kJ) including 10 kilograms (22 lb) of bread, but as there was limited grain the bread ration was only 8.5 kilograms (19 lb).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] However, as there was only sufficient bread for about 50% of this "called up" ration, the total deficiency was about 50%, not 15% as stated in a ministerial reply in the British Parliament on 11 December.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] So only about 770 calories (3,200 kJ) would have been supplied, and he said the German winter ration would be 1,000 calories (4,200 kJ) as the recent increase was "largely mythical".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] His book includes photos taken on the visit and critical letters and newspaper articles by him published in several British newspapers; *The Times, the Daily Herald, the Manchester Guardian*, etc.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Some occupation soldiers took advantage of the desperate food situation by exploiting their ample supply of food and cigarettes (the currency of the black market) to get to the local German girls as what became known as *frau bait* (*The New York Times*, 25 June 1945).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Some soldiers still felt the girls were the enemy, but used them for sex nevertheless.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The often destitute mothers of the resulting children usually received no child support.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In the earliest stages of the occupation, U.S. soldiers were not allowed to pay maintenance for a child they admitted having fathered, since to do so was considered "aiding the enemy".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Marriages between white U.S. soldiers and Austrian women were not permitted until January 1946, and with German women until December 1946.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The children of African-American soldiers, commonly called *Negermischlinge* ("Negro half-breeds"), comprising about three percent of the total number of children fathered by GIs, were particularly disadvantaged because of their inability to conceal the foreign identity of their fathers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] For many white U.S. soldiers of this era, miscegenation even with an "enemy" white population was regarded as an intolerable outrage.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Even in the rare cases where an African-American soldier was willing to take responsibility for fathering a child, until 1948 the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The mothers of the children would often face particularly harsh ostracism.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Between 1950 and 1955, the Allied High Commission for Germany prohibited "proceedings to establish paternity or liability for maintenance of children." Even after the lifting of the ban West German courts had little power over American soldiers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] While Allied servicemen were ordered to obey local laws while in Germany, soldiers could not be prosecuted by German courts for crimes committed against German citizens except as authorised by the occupation authorities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Invariably, when a soldier was accused of criminal behaviour the occupation authorities preferred to handle the matter within the military justice system.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] This sometimes led to harsher punishments than would have been available under German law – in particular, U.S. servicemen could be executed if court-martialed and convicted of rape.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The last Allied war advances into Germany and Allied occupation plans were affected by rumors of the Nazi Werwolf plan for insurgency, but actual insurgent efforts were minimal.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Numerous historians, including Antony Beevor and Earl F.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Ziemke, Golo Mann, and Richard Bessel, have observed that widespread resistance never really materialized.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] The threat was nevertheless taken seriously by the Allies, with the Soviets using unfounded suspicions of Werwolf activity as a pretext to tighten police control and secure forced labor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Perry Biddiscombe, while also characterizing German resistance as minor, argues that they caused tens of millions of dollars of property damage, and estimates the total death toll due to Werwolf actions and the resulting reprisals as 3,000–5,000.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Particularly in the initial stages of the occupation, American military authorities are known to have responded harshly to such attacks, including through the application of the death penalty against individuals caught having killed or attacked US soldiers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] See: Capital punishment by the United States military.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Hungary, which had been allied with Germany and whose population was opposed to an expulsion of the German minority, tried to resist the transfer.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Hungary had to yield to the pressure exerted mainly by the Soviet Union and by the Allied Control Council.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Millions of people were expelled from former eastern territories of Germany, Poland, Czechoslovakia, Hungary and elsewhere to the occupation zones of the UK, US, and USSR, which agreed in the Potsdam Agreement to absorb the post-war expellees into their zones.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Many remained in refugee camps for a long time.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] Some Germans remained in the Soviet Union and were used for forced labour for a period of years.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] France was not invited to the Potsdam Conference.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] As a result, it chose to adopt some decisions of the Potsdam Agreements and to dismiss others.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] France maintained the position that it did not approve post-war expulsions and that therefore it was not responsible to accommodate and nourish the destitute expellees in its zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] While the few war-related refugees who had reached the area to become the French zone before July 1945 were taken care of, the French military government for Germany refused to absorb post-war expellees deported from the East into its zone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] In December 1946, the French military government for Germany absorbed into its zone German refugees from Denmark, where 250,000 Germans had found a refuge from the Soviets by sea vessels between February and May 1945.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/allied-occupied-germany] These clearly were war-related refugees from the eastern parts of Germany however, and not post-war expellees.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] Von Schoeler joined the Free Democratic Party of Germany (FDP) aged 18.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] He served in the Bundestag between 1972 and 1982.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] On 16 December 1976, von Schoeler was chosen to be the Parliamentary State Secretary for the Minister of the Interior, Werner Maihofer.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] He served in this position until 17 September 1982, when the ruling SPD-FDP coalition collapsed.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] Von Schoeler was one of several FDP politicians who left the party in what was known as the "Wende" ("turning point").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] After leaving the FDP to join the SPD, von Schoeler attempted to re-enter the Bundestag on the SPD party list, but failed and was not elected.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] In 1984, von Schoeler joined the Hessen State Cabinet of Holger Börner as the State Secretary of the Interior.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] After the SPD was defeated in the 1987 elections, von Schoeler left this position.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] After a brief stint working for Sony, Von Schoeler became the Head of Personnel, Legal and Economic Affairs in Frankfurt am Main in 1989, and replaced Volker Hauff as Mayor of Frankfurt in 1991.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] When he became mayor, von Schoeler was the youngest mayor in the history of Frankfurt at 43 years old.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] As Mayor of Frankfurt von Schoeler led Frankfurt's campaign to be the location for the future European Central Bank.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] He encouraged the internationalisation of the Messe Frankfurt trade fair.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] He also arranged for Frankfurt to become the first major German city to allow a private network operate to set up a private fibre-optic network in the city area.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] In 1995, the SPD-Green Party coalition which held power in Frankfurt fell apart; von Schoeler then left office to pave the way for new elections, and lost in the first direct election for Mayor of Frankfurt with 45.9% of the vote to Petra Roth's 51.1%.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] Roth went on to serve as mayor until 2012.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] Since 2009, von Schoeler has been involved in the Society of Friends and Patrons of the Jewish Museum Frankfurt, and was chairman of the board until 2021.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/andreas-von-schoeler] Under von Schoeler's leadership the museum expanded significantly.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Homburg was the capital of the Landgraviate of Hesse-Homburg until its incorporation into the Kingdom of Prussia in 1866.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] During the time of the German Empire, Emperor Wilhelm II made the town's castle his summer residence.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The town has become best known for its mineral springs and spa (hence the prefix *Bad*, meaning "bath"), and for its casino.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] As of 2004, the town used the marketing slogan *Champagnerluft und Tradition* (Champagne air and tradition).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] As of 2021, Bad Homburg was one of the wealthiest towns in Germany (while the Hochtaunuskreis itself and the Landkreis Starnberg in Bavaria regularly vie for the title of the wealthiest district in Germany).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Local tradition holds that Bad Homburg's documented history began with the mention of the *Villa Tidenheim* in the Lorsch codex, associated with the year 782.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] This *Villa Tidenheim* was equated with the historic city center, which is called Dietigheim.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The local historian Rüdiger Kurth has questioned this traditional story based on his study of written sources and local factors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 2002, Kurth initiated archaeological excavations by the University of Frankfurt, managed by Professor Joachim Henning.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The excavations showed no evidence of settlement between the beginning of the Christian Era and the 13th century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The historical record in the Eberbach chronicles (*Eberbacher Zeugenreihe*), which mentions Wortwin (or Ortwin) von Hohenberch as Homburg's founder about 1180, is the first solid evidence of the town's existence.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] As early as 1962, in an excavation under the Hirschgang wing of Bad Homburg Castle, two burnt layers were discovered, which the archaeologist Günther Binding interpreted as evidence of two former castles having occupied the site in succession and burnt down.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Further digs by the University of Frankfurt at Bad Homburg Castle in April 2006, again initiated by Kurth and managed by Prof.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Henning, revealed only a single burnt layer, from a half-timbered building, possibly a castle with towers, which was dated from ceramic finds to the 12th or 13th century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Most likely this building had an association with Wortwin's "castle".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] A further cultural layer from an even earlier time may lie beneath these remains.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Investigations using carbon-14 dating and micromorphological analysis will show whether the dating can be made more precise.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Homberg acquired market rights about 1330, but the document granting these rights is said to have been lost.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The town's name, "Homburg", is derived from the *Hohenberg* Castle.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The suffix "vor der Höhe" was probably first recorded in a document of 1399.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The designation *Bad* was conferred in 1912.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 1622, Homburg became the capital of the Landgraviate of Hesse-Homburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The first landgrave of Hessen-Homburg was Friedrich I of Hessen-Homburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Friedrich II (1680–1708) attained fame as Prince of Homburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 1866, as a result of the Austro-Prussian War, Homburg became Prussian territory.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] With the beginning of the spa industry in the town in the mid-19th century, Homburg became an internationally famous spa town.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Bad Homburg was favoured particularly by Russian nobility.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The spa industry began with the discovery of the *Elisabethenbrunnen* ("Princess Elizabeth's spring") in 1834.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The first spa building and the first casino in Homburg were built in 1841–1842 by the brothers François (1806–1877) and Louis Blanc (1806–1852), who later owned the Monte Carlo Casino.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 1860, the town was connected with Frankfurt by a railway line.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 1888, Homburg became known throughout the German Empire because Kaiser Wilhelm II made its castle his imperial summer residence.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] He later financed the building of the Church of the Redeemer (Erlöserkirche) nearby.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The emperor's mother also lived there for several years.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Edward VII of the United Kingdom was often a guest; it was he who introduced the Homburg hat and turned-up trousers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Edward took fasting cures at Homburg 32 times.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The Bad Homburger Golf Club in the *Röderweisen* in Dornholzhausen – now part of Bad Homburg – is Germany's oldest golf club.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] It had its beginnings in the Bad Homburg spa park, where the old clubhouse and even playable parts of the old golf course can still be found.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Not far away stands the Russian Chapel, properly called All Saints' Church, an Eastern Orthodox church whose cornerstone was laid by the Russian imperial couple on 16 October 1896, although they did not attend the church's consecration almost three years later.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] King Chulalongkorn of Siam (Thailand) sent a garden pavilion in gratitude for a successful cure.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Horex was a well known German motorcycle brand of the "Horex—Fahrzeugbau AG", founded in 1923 in Bad Homburg by Fritz Kleemann.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 1335, permission was given by Emperor Louis IV to Gottfried von Eppstein to settle 10 Jews in each of the localities of Eppstein, Homburg, and Steinheim; it is uncertain, however, whether any Jews settled in Homburg at that time.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Evidence for the existence of a permanent Jewish settlement in Homburg is found only at the beginning of the 16th century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Until 1600 it consisted of 2 or 3 families, and by 1632 these had increased to 16.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The first Jewish cemetery was purchased in the 17th century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The community continued to grow so rapidly that in 1703 the landgrave Frederick II of Hesse decided on the construction of a special Judengasse (Jewish quarter).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] A synagogue, built in 1731, was replaced by a new one in 1867.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The Jewish community of Homburg was originally part of the jurisdiction of the rabbinate of Friedberg but began to appoint its own rabbis in the 19th century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] A Hebrew printing house was located in Homburg by Seligmann ben Hirz Reis from 1710 until 1713, when he relocated to Offenbach am Main.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Among other items, he published Jacob ibn Ḥabib's *Ein Ya'akov* (1712).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Hebrew printing was resumed there in 1724 by Samson ben Salman Hanau but lack of capital limited his output.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The press was acquired in 1736 by Aaron ben Ẓevi Dessau whose publications included the *Shulhan Arukh (Ḥoshen Mishpat)* with commentary (1742).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The press was sold in 1748 and transferred in 1749 to Roedelheim.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] At the beginning of the 20th century, the spa of Homburg became a meeting place of Russian-Jewish intellectuals.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Of the 74 Jews who remained on 17 May 1939, 42 were deported in 1942/1943 to Concentration Camps, never to return.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] While the spa business experienced a long-term decrease after the two world wars, the town gained importance by becoming the site for headquarters of various authorities and administrative bodies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] By autumn 1946, the military government had already ordered the founding of bizonal authorities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Bad Homburg was chosen as the seat of the financial administrative centre.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] On 23 July 1947, the Bizone Economic Council instituted the "Special Money and Credit Centre" here in preparation for currency reform.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The centre was managed by Ludwig Erhard, the later *Bundeskanzler*.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In the 20th century, Bad Homburg became a favourite residential area among the upper classes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] On 30 November 1989, Alfred Herrhausen, the manager of Deutsche Bank, was killed and his driver was injured by a car bomb in Bad Homburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] It is alleged that this was an attack by the Red Army Faction, though this has never been proven.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Bad Homburg's civic coat of arms was granted in 1903 but is said to date from the 15th century on the basis of seals known from that time, although they show a saltire rather than the two adzes seen today (the saltire might be two unclear adzes).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The reason for the adzes in the arms is not known; it is possibly dialectal canting.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The colours, with silver adzes in a blue field, have been in use at least since 1621.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Baseball club Bad Homburg Hornets play in Germany's 2.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] Bundesliga, having competed in the country's first division until 2018.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The Bad Homburg Open is a WTA 500 tennis tournament held in the town in honour of its long legacy of playing and developing the sport.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] The inaugural Bad Homburg Open was held as WTA 250 event in 2021 and played on grass at the TC Bad Homburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] German player Angelique Kerber won the event.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] In 2024, it was upgraded to a WTA 500 event.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bad-homburg] **^** In 1953, the town adopted the ethnic Germans driven out of this town, later also partnership.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] During 2014, the average circulation of *Die Welt* was approximately 180,000.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The paper may be obtained in more than 130 countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] Daily regional editions appear in Berlin and Hamburg.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] A daily regional supplement also appears in Bremen.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The main editorial office is in Berlin, in conjunction with the *Berliner Morgenpost*.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] From 2004 to 2019, the newspaper also published a compact edition entitled *Welt Kompakt*, a 32-page cut-down version of the main broadsheet targeted to a younger public.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The paper does not appear on Sundays, but the linked publication *Welt am Sonntag* takes its place.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The 1993 circulation of the paper was 209,677 copies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] At its peak in the occupation period, it had a circulation of approximately a million.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] In 2002 the paper experimented with a Bavarian edition.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] In November 2010, a redesign for the newspaper was launched, featuring a new logo with a dark blue globe, a reduced number of columns from seven to six, and typography based on the Freight typeface designed by Joshua Darden.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] *Welt Kompakt* was also redesigned to use that typeface.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] On 2 May 2014, the Swiss German business magazine *Bilanz* began to be published as a monthly supplement of *Die Welt*.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] On 18 January 2018, the German television channel N24 changed its name to Welt.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] Jan Philipp Burgard was forced to resign as editor in chief in January 2026; he was replaced by Helge Fuhst.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The paper was banned in Egypt in February 2008 due to the publication of cartoons depicting the Islamic prophet Muhammad.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] From 1999 to 2019, the *Die Welt* book supplement *Die Literarische Welt* ("The Literary World") presented an annual €10,000 literature prize available to international authors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] The award is in honor of Willy Haas who founded *Die Literarische Welt* in 1925.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] During the COVID-19-pandemic, the newspaper was criticized by the Amadeu Antonio Foundation for adopting right-wing populist talking points and publishing misinformation about COVID-19.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] Liz Fekete criticized the newspaper in 2024 for uncritically adopting Israel's talking points on the Middle East conflict, to the disadvantage of Palestinians, and spreading false information about the prevalence of antisemitism among immigrants.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/die-welt] In December 2024, opinion department chief Eva Marie Kogel left *Die Welt* protesting the publication of an op-ed by Elon Musk that supports AfD.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] By contrast, in an indirect election, the voters elect a body which in turn elects the officeholder in question.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] In other settings, politicians and office holders are appointed.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] In a double direct election, the elected representative serves on two councils, typically a lower-tier council of a municipality and an upper-tier council of a regional district or municipality.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] The idea that heads of state be elected directly by the people progressed slowly throughout the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] This differs from parliamentary systems where executives derive power from the legislative body.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Many African nations have moved from parliamentary to presidential systems.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Regardless of constitutional structures, presidents often have immense power over other political decision-making bodies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Given this power, much of the political violence around elections stems from the elections of presidents.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Additionally, recent coups and conflict have postponed direct presidential elections in several African countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] The overwhelming majority of democracies in Asia are parliamentary, rather than presidential systems.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Based on constitutional design, the Philippines is the only head of state elected by popular vote.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] South Korea has an even stronger presidential system as well a directly-elected head of state based on changes in 1987 to its constitution.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] The first major European country to use direct elections was France (1848).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] However, if no candidate received a majority of the vote the National Assembly chose the winner from the top five candidates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] As the so-called Second Republic only lasted for one presidential term, this never happened.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Germany (the Weimar Republic) was the first European country to use direct election of a president without intervention by the legislature.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Both these systems were replaced by autocratic systems within a number of years, with indirect presidential elections instated with the restoration of democracy (in 1871 and 1949, in West Germany, respectively).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Currently, Europe has a mix of parliamentary republics, presidential republics, where the president is elected directly by the people, and semi-presidential republics - including contemporary France - which have a president elected directly and a prime minister responsible to the parliament.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] A major debate exists regarding colonial legacies and the promotion of democracy around the world.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] In terms of direct elections, former British colonies are less likely to hold direct elections for heads of state.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Additionally no monarchies have direct elections for head of state since by definition the head of state is unelected.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] The conceptual origins of direct presidential elections stem from the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Constitution (1787) through the Electoral College.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] The Framers intended for a small group of electors, through methods determined by each state, to elect the president.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Thus in practice this represents a form of indirect election.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Bolstered by opposition groups, institutional and constitutional change in the 1980s and 1990s led to direct elections of presidents in many South American countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] These changes created centralized power in presidential positions, often blurring the line of separation of powers and making them powerful decision-makers over the legislature and cabinet.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] A common political debate, particularly as countries consider governmental reforms, is whether or not direct elections of heads of state strengthen democratic practices among citizens.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Selection mechanisms for heads of state can lead to varying outcomes in terms of voter interest, turnout, and overall engagement.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] For example, some scholars argue that direct elections will mobilize voters and increase their trust in the political process, particularly in emerging democracies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/direct-election] Others note that frequent direct elections may decrease turnout due to voter fatigue and apathy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The **European Central Bank** (**ECB**) is the central component of the Eurosystem and the European System of Central Banks (ESCB) as well as one of seven institutions of the European Union.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It is one of the world's most important central banks, heading a system with a combined balance sheet of close to €7 trillion.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB Governing Council makes monetary policy for the Eurozone and the European Union, administers the foreign exchange reserves of EU member states, engages in foreign exchange operations, and defines the intermediate monetary objectives and key interest rate of the EU.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB Executive Board enforces the policies and decisions of the Governing Council, and may direct the national central banks when doing so.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB has the exclusive right to authorise the issuance of euro banknotes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Member states can issue euro coins, but the volume must be approved by the ECB beforehand.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The bank also operates the T2 payments system.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB was established by the Treaty of Amsterdam in May 1999 with the purpose of guaranteeing and maintaining price stability.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 1 December 2009, the Treaty of Lisbon became effective and the bank gained the official status of an EU institution.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] When the ECB was created, it covered a Eurozone of eleven members.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Since then, Greece joined in January 2001, Slovenia in January 2007, Cyprus and Malta in January 2008, Slovakia in January 2009, Estonia in January 2011, Latvia in January 2014, Lithuania in January 2015, Croatia in January 2023, and Bulgaria in January 2026.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The current president of the ECB is Christine Lagarde.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Seated in Frankfurt, Germany, the bank formerly occupied the Eurotower prior to the construction of its new seat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB is directly governed by European Union law.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Its capital stock, worth €11 billion, is owned by all 27 central banks of the EU member states as shareholders.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The initial capital allocation key was determined in 1998 on the basis of the states' population and GDP, but the capital key has been readjusted since.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Shares in the ECB are not transferable and cannot be used as collateral.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The European Central Bank is the *de facto* successor of the European Monetary Institute (EMI).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The EMI was established at the start of the second stage of the EU's Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) to handle the transitional issues of states adopting the euro and prepare for the creation of the ECB and European System of Central Banks (ESCB).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The EMI itself took over from the earlier European Monetary Cooperation Fund (EMCF).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB formally replaced the EMI on 1 June 1998 by virtue of the Treaty on European Union (TEU, Treaty of Maastricht), however it did not exercise its full powers until the introduction of the euro on 1 January 1999, signalling the third stage of EMU.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The bank was the final institution needed for EMU, as outlined by the EMU reports of Pierre Werner and President Jacques Delors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It was established on 1 June 1998 The first President of the Bank was Wim Duisenberg, the former president of the Dutch central bank and the European Monetary Institute.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] While Duisenberg had been the head of the EMI (taking over from Alexandre Lamfalussy of Belgium) just before the ECB came into existence, the French government wanted Jean-Claude Trichet, former head of the French central bank, to be the ECB's first president.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The French argued that since the ECB was to be located in Germany, its president should be French.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This was opposed by the German, Dutch and Belgian governments who saw Duisenberg as a guarantor of a strong euro.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Tensions were abated by a gentleman's agreement in which Duisenberg would stand down before the end of his mandate, to be replaced by Trichet.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Trichet replaced Duisenberg as president in November 2003.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Until 2007, the ECB had very successfully managed to maintain inflation close but below 2%.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The European Central Bank underwent through a deep internal transformation as it faced the 2008 financial crisis and the Euro area crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The *Euro area crisis* began after Greece's new elected government uncovered the real level of indebtedness and budget deficit and warned EU institutions of the imminent danger of a Greek sovereign default.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Foreseeing a possible sovereign default in the eurozone, the general public, international and European institutions, and the financial community reassessed the economic situation and creditworthiness of some Eurozone member states.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Consequently, sovereign bonds yields of several Eurozone countries started to rise sharply.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This provoked a self-fulfilling panic on financial markets: the more Greek bonds yields rose, the more likely a default became possible, the more bond yields increased in turn.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This panic was also aggravated because of the reluctance of the ECB to react and intervene on sovereign bond markets for two reasons.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] First, because the ECB's legal framework normally forbids the purchase of sovereign bonds in the primary market (Article 123.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] TFEU), An over-interpretation of this limitation, inhibited the ECB from implementing quantitative easing like the Federal Reserve and the Bank of England did as soon as 2008, which played an important role in stabilizing markets.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Secondly, a decision by the ECB made in 2005 introduced a minimum credit rating (BBB-) for all Eurozone sovereign bonds to be eligible as collateral to the ECB's open market operations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This meant that if a private rating agencies were to downgrade a sovereign bond below that threshold, many banks would suddenly become illiquid because they would lose access to ECB refinancing operations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] According to former member of the governing council of the ECB Athanasios Orphanides, this change in the ECB's collateral framework "planted the seed" of the euro crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Faced with those regulatory constraints, the ECB led by Jean-Claude Trichet in 2010 was reluctant to intervene to calm down financial markets.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Up until 6 May 2010, Trichet formally denied at several press conferences the possibility of the ECB to embark into sovereign bonds purchases, even though Greece, Ireland, Portugal, Spain and Italy faced waves of credit rating downgrades and increasing interest rate spreads.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In a remarkable u-turn, the ECB announced on 10 May 2010, the launch of a "Securities Market Programme" (SMP) which involved the discretionary purchase of sovereign bonds in secondary markets.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Extraordinarily, the decision was taken by the Governing Council during a teleconference call only three days after the ECB's usual meeting of 6 May (when Trichet still denied the possibility of purchasing sovereign bonds).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although at first limited to the debt of Greece, Ireland and Portugal, the bulk of the ECB's bond buying eventually consisted of Spanish and Italian debt.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These purchases were intended to dampen international speculation against stressed countries, and thus avoid a contagion of the Greek crisis towards other Eurozone countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The assumption—largely justified—was that speculative activity would decrease over time and the value of the assets increase.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although SMP purchases did inject liquidity into financial markets, all of these injections were "sterilized" through weekly liquidity absorption.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] So the operation was net neutral in liquidity terms (though this was of little practical importance since normal monetary policy operations were ensuring unlimited supplies of liquidity at the main policy interest rate).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In September 2011, ECB's Board member Jürgen Stark, resigned in protest against the "Securities Market Programme" which involved the purchase of sovereign bonds from Southern member states, a move that he considered as equivalent to monetary financing, which is prohibited by the EU Treaty.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The *Financial Times Deutschland* referred to this episode as "the end of the ECB as we know it", referring to its hitherto perceived "hawkish" stance on inflation and its historical Deutsche Bundesbank influence.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] As of 18 June 2012, the ECB in total had spent €212.1bn (equal to 2.2% of the Eurozone GDP) for bond purchases covering outright debt, as part of the Securities Markets Programme.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Controversially, the ECB made substantial profits out of SMP, which were largely redistributed to Eurozone countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In 2013, the Eurogroup decided to refund those profits to Greece, however, the payments were suspended from 2014 until 2017 over the conflict between Yanis Varoufakis and ministers of the Eurogroup.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In 2018, profits refunds were reinstalled by the Eurogroup.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, several NGOs complained that a substantial part of the ECB profits would never be refunded to Greece.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB played a controversial role in the "Troika" by rejecting most forms of debt restructuring of public and bank debts, and pressing governments to adopt bailout programmes and structural reforms through secret letters to Italian, Spanish, Greek and Irish governments.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It has further been accused of interfering in the Greek referendum of July 2015 by constraining liquidity to Greek commercial banks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In November 2010, reflecting the huge increase in borrowing, including the cover the cost of having guaranteed the liabilities of banks, the cost of borrowing in the private financial markets had become prohibitive for the Irish government.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Meanwhile, Anglo used the promissory note as collateral for its emergency loan (ELA) from the Central Bank.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This enabled Anglo to repay its depositors and bondholders.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It became clear later that the ECB played a key role in making sure the Irish government did not let Anglo default on its debts, to avoid financial instability risks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In addition, the ECB insisted that no debt restructuring (or bail-in) should be applied to the nationalized banks' bondholders, a measure which could have saved Ireland 8 billion euros.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] During 2012, the ECB pressed for an early end to the ELA, and this situation was resolved with the liquidation of the successor institution IBRC in February 2013.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The promissory note was exchanged for much longer term marketable floating rate notes which were disposed of by the Central Bank over the following decade.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In April 2011, the ECB raised interest rates for the first time since 2008 from 1% to 1.25%, with a further increase to 1.50% in July 2011.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, in 2012–2013 the ECB sharply lowered interest rates to encourage economic growth, reaching the historically low 0.25% in November 2013.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Soon after the rates were cut to 0.15%, then on 4 September 2014 the central bank reduced the rates by two-thirds from 0.15% to 0.05%.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Recently, the interest rates were further reduced reaching 0.00%, the lowest rates on record.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In a report adopted on 13 March 2014, the European Parliament criticized the "potential conflict of interest between the current role of the ECB in the Troika as 'technical advisor' and its position as a creditor of the four Member States, as well as its mandate under the Treaty".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The report was led by Austrian right-wing MEP Othmar Karas and French Socialist MEP Liem Hoang Ngoc.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 1 November 2011, Mario Draghi replaced Jean-Claude Trichet as President of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This change in leadership also marks the start of a new era under which the ECB will become more and more interventionist and eventually ended the Euro area crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Draghi's presidency started with the impressive launch of a new round of 1% interest loans with a term of three years (36 months) – the **Long-term Refinancing operations (LTRO)**.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Under this programme, 523 Banks tapped as much as €489.2 bn (US$640 bn).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Observers were surprised by the volume of loans made when it was implemented.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] By far biggest amount of €325bn was tapped by banks in Greece, Ireland, Italy and Spain.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although those LTROs loans did not directly benefit EU governments, it effectively allowed banks to do a carry trade, by lending off the LTROs loans to governments with an interest margin.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The operation also facilitated the rollover of €200bn of maturing bank debts in the first three months of 2012.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Facing renewed fears about sovereigns in the eurozone continued Mario Draghi made a decisive speech in London, by declaring that the ECB "...is ready to do ***whatever it takes*** to preserve the Euro.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Following up on Draghi's speech, on 6 September 2012 the ECB announced the **Outright Monetary Transactions** programme (OMT).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Unlike the previous SMP programme, OMT has no ex-ante time or size limit.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the activation of the purchases remains conditioned to the adherence by the benefitting country to an adjustment programme to the ESM.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The program was adopted with near unanimity, the Bundesbank president Jens Weidmann being the sole member of the ECB's Governing Council to vote against it.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Even if OMT was never actually implemented until today, it made the "Whatever it takes" pledge credible and significantly contributed to stabilizing financial markets and ending the sovereign debt crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] According to various sources, the OMT programme and "whatever it takes" speeches were made possible because EU leaders previously agreed to build the banking union.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In November 2014, the bank moved into its new premises, while the Eurotower building was dedicated to hosting the newly established supervisory activities of the ECB under European Banking Supervision.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although the Euro area crisis was almost solved by 2014, the ECB started to face a repeated decline in the Eurozone inflation rate, indicating that the economy was going towards a deflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Responding to this threat, the ECB announced on 4 September 2014 the launch of two bond buying purchases programmes: the Covered Bond Purchasing Programme (CBPP3) and Asset-Backed Securities Programme (ABSPP).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 22 January 2015, the ECB announced an extension of those programmes within a full-fledge "quantitative easing" programme which also included sovereign bonds, to the tune of 60 billion euros per month up until at least September 2016.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The programme was started on 9 March 2015.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 8 June 2016, the ECB added corporate bonds to its asset purchases portfolio with the launch of the corporate sector purchase programme (CSPP).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Under this programme, it conducted the net purchase of corporate bonds until January 2019 to reach about €177 billion.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] While the programme was halted for 11 months in January 2019, the ECB restarted net purchases in November 2019.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The PSPP-implementing decision has been considered an act ultra vires by the ECB as it was too arbitrary and lacks reasoning in ints proportionality assessment.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This ruling by the German Constitutional Court comes at a difficult time for the ECB as it was at the time considering expanding the PEPP.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ruling also reflects the mistrust within some parts of Germany in the ECB, which is seen there as an institution that bails out profligate Southern European countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Moreover, this ruling also highlights the vital problem on the euro area architecture, as the range of instruments can use to fulfil its mandate remains unclear.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] As of 2021, the size of the ECB's quantitative easing programme had reached 2947 billion euros.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The long term refinancing operations (LTRO) are regular open market operations providing financing to credit institutions for periods up to four years.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] They aim at favoring lending conditions to the private sector and more generally stimulating bank lending to the real economy, thereby fostering growth.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In December 2011 and January 2012, in the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis, the ECB implemented two LTROs, injecting over €1000 billion of liquidity in the Eurozone financial system.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] They were later criticized for their inability to revive growth and to help truly revive the real economy, despite having stabilized the Eurozone's financial institutions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These critics and deficiencies brought the ECB to instigate targeted long term refinancing operations (TLTROs), first in September and later in December 2014.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These complementary programs imposed conditionality on the LTROs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The TLTROs provided low cost financing to participating banks, under the condition that they reached certain targets in terms of lending to firms and households.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The participating banks were thus more incited to lend to the real economy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] A third wave of TLTRO's was announced on 7 March 2019, namely the TLTRO III.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Under TLTRO III, the interest rate was set at −0.5% below the deposit facility rate (DFR), under condition that banks reached a specific lending performance threshold.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The TLTRO III programme was successful to stimulate credit growth.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In July 2019, EU leaders nominated Christine Lagarde to replace Mario Draghi as ECB President.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Lagarde resigned from her position as managing director of the International Monetary Fund in July 2019 and formally took over the ECB's presidency on 1 November 2019.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Lagarde immediately signalled a change of style in the ECB's leadership.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] She embarked the ECB on a strategic review of the ECB's monetary policy strategy, an exercise the ECB had not done for 17 years.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The onset of the COVID-19 pandemic precipitated an unprecedented crisis, profoundly impacting global public health, economies, and societal structures on an unparalleled scale.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The crisis led to renewed tensions in European sovereign bonds markets, marked by a growing spreads between the interest rates paid by Eurozone member states, which spurred concerns about the Euro area crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 12 March 2020, the ECB announced a set of policy measures such as an additional package of net asset purchases of €120 billion by the end of 2020 under the already existing APP, and more favorable terms on the TLTRO III.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] During the press conference, Christine Lagarde declared that the ECB "[...] is not here to close spreads." This particular statement triggered a sudden negative reaction on financial markets, with a widening of yield spreads in Spain, Italy and Greece.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This announcement led to an immediate reboot in stock prices and came one day after the spike of sovereign risk spreads.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The PEPP was designed as a typical "quantitative easing" policy, under which the ECB is able to purchase securities from the private and public sector in a flexible manner.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The purpose of the PEPP was to stabilize sovereign bonds yields to low and stable levels, thus preventing self-fulfilling panics in financial markets as was the case during the Euro area crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The PEPP was established as a separate purchase programme alongside the pre-existing Asset Purchase Programme (APP) with the sole purpose to respond to the economic and financial consequences of the COVID-19 crisis, and in particular prevent market fragmentations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] While very similar, contrary to the APP, the ECB decided to allow itself to deviate from the capital key.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This temporal flexibility from the capital key meant that the ECB could more effectively prevent the rise of Italian and Spanish yield spreads.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Assets meeting the eligibility criteria of the APP were also eligible under the PEPP.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the pool of assets eligible under the PEPP was broader than the usual ECB collateral eligibility framework.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] For instance, Greek sovereign bonds could be purchased by the ECB under this programme, despite having a credit ratings below the usual investment grade requirement.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This waiver was given based on several considerations from the ECB: there was a need to alleviate the pressures stemming from the pandemic on the Greek financial markets; Greece was already and would be closely monitored by giving the waiver; and Greece regained market access.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Non-financial commercial paper with a remaining maturity of at least 28 days were also eligible for purchase under the PEPP.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 4 June 2020, the ECB announced it would expand the PEPP by another €600 billion, as it became clear that the pandemic would continue to harm European economies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Half a year later, on 10 December 2020, the ECB announced its final expansion of the PEPP worth another €500 billion, totalling the final PEPP to €1.850 trillion, corresponding to 15.4% of the euro-area GDP of 2019.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In December 2021, the ECB announced that it would discontinue net purchases under the PEPP as from the end of March 2022 and that it intended to reinvest the principal payments from maturing securities at least until the end of 2024.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 31 March 2022, at the end of the net purchases, the net purchases amounted to €1.718 billion, of which €1.665 billion is invested in public sector securities and €52 billion in private sector securities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Of the total €1.850 billion available under the PEPP, 93% of the full envelope wase used, due to indications of decreased financial stress in the Euro Area, mainly thanks to relaxation of COVID restrictions and the reopening of European markets.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Overall, the PEPP programme was widely welcomed by market participants and European policy makers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However in March 2021, a group of German economists and lawyers filed a lawsuit against the PEPP at the German Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On 30 April 2020, the ECB Governing council introduced additional measures to support the economy during the COVID-19 pandemic, including PELTROs and new modalities for the TLTROs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] First, the ECB made several adjustments to the framework of its TLTRO III.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] A key change was that the ECB also reduced the interest rate applied to these open market operations to a rate going as low as −1% for the banks meeting the lending threshold of 0%.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] With the TLTRO III, the participating banks were thus enabled to borrow at lower interest rates than those paid on their excess reserve.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Another key change was thet ECB's decision to expand bank's borrowing allowance under TLTRO III from 30% to 50%, then up to 55% of their portfolio of loans to firms and households.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Second, the ECB introduced pandemic emergency long-term refinancing operations (PELTROs).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The market operations are similar to the TLTRO III, but are conduced in a more frequent basis in order to ensure smooth liquidity provision to the market.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] During the pandemic, these monetary responses proved essential.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In their absence, a credit crunch would normally have taken place.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Indeed, increase in demand traditionally translates in a rise of borrowing costs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Reports from various member states central banks on the matter indicate that loans supply by participating banks has indeed expanded, in line with the ECB policy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Accordingly, thorough academic studies have confirmed the actual enhancement of financing conditions and the avoidance of credit scarcity.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In fact, the credit to firms attained unprecedented levels when from March to May 2020, it increased by €250 billion on aggregate.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Furthermore, analysts observed that even non-participating banks (to the TLTROs and PELTROs) benefited from it in parallel manners.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The Transmission Protection Instrument (TPI) is a tool the ECB could use to ensure monetary policy decisions are smoothly transmitted across all euro area countries, introduced on 21 July 2022.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Contrary to the PEPP and the APP, the TPI does not have an *ex ante* upper limit on the purchase of securities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although the ECB has stated it would primarily buy only government bonds on the secondary market maturing between 1 and 10 years, the bonds purchased fall under the complete discretion of the ECB and does not necessarily follow the capital key, and private securities could be considered as well.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Stick to commitments made under the Recovery and Resilience Facility, proving that the government follows sound and sustainable macroeconomic policies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The conditions for government bonds to be eligible under the TPI draw heavily on the macroeconomic governance, and making sure that politicians do not take decisions that facilitate speculation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The decision by the ECB to support a country by using the TPI will depend on the severity of the risks a country faces.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Government debt should thus be sustainable to be eligible for TPI purchases.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] If the aforementioned conditions are met, the ECB could decide to activate the TPI.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Purchases will be ended under the TPI either due to increased transmission of monetary policy or the risks have proven to be country-specific.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] So far, the TPI has not been deployed yet.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the relationship between the PEPP and the TPI raises questions as the PEPP would remain the first line of defence against transmission risks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The creation of the TPI seems legally vulnerably: problems in the Euro Area are common and recurring, but it is not automatically the argument to invent a whole new anti-fragmentation tool.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] With the TPI, the ECB can put pressure on countries by assessing publicly if they are eligible for the TPI, that is assessing whether the government has conducted adequate fiscal policies and structural reforms to deserve the support of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This endangers the politic neutrality of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] If ever deployed, the usage of the TPI will spark controversy as the conditions to be deployed are not watertight.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] As a consequence of the COVID-19 crisis, the ECB extended the duration of the strategy review until September 2021.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB also said it would carry out another strategy review in 2025.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In the summer of 2021, coinciding with the European Central Bank's announcement of its revised monetary policy framework and its initiative for climate action, the eurozone witnessed a notable inflationary surge.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This resurgence of inflation continued to escalate over the following year, culminating in inflation rates reaching double digits for the first time since the 1970s, a year after the ECB's strategic updates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The inflation rate reached an unprecedented peak of 4.9% in November 2021, marking the highest level since the introduction of the euro.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The new era of inflation prompted a significant shift in the European Central Bank's framing compared to its stance in the 2000s.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Initially, from its inception until the 2008 financial crisis, the ECB's primary objective was price stability, adhering to strict institutional rules that minimized policy trade-offs with other goals beyond price stability.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This approach was rooted in the "Central Bank Independence template", advocating that central bank's limited role to price stability and its independence were optimal.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the post-financial crisis landscape, especially during the Euro area crisis and subsequent economic stagnation era, necessitated a substantial revision in the ECB's strategy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB moved away from its original Central Bank Independence template, leading to a blurring of its objective hierarchy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It adopted new strategies such as acting as a lender of last resort for the banking system and fostering growth through very low interest rates and extensive asset purchase programs, which were designed to help stabilize specific market segments and in the end revive growth.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In 2021, the European Central Bank embraced a significant strategic pivot by adopting its Climate Action Plan along with a new monetary policy strategy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This shift aimed to institutionalize the ECB's evolving role, moving beyond the singular focus on price stability—a policy shaped largely by the aftermath of the Euro area crisis.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Instead, the ECB began acknowledging its multifaceted responsibilities, which now include maintaining financial stability, supporting economic growth, and addressing climate-related objectives.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, with the surging of inflation in 2021, some wondered as to whether the European Central Bank would revert to its foundational role, predominantly focused on chasing the "inflation monsters".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The term "inflation monsters'' echoes the 2010 video of the ECB where two young people are facing a blue inflation monster unleashing banknotes and threatening to wreck the economy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Nevertheless, ECB policymakers effectively drew connections between the Central Bank Independence (CBI) framework and the experiences of the stagflation era to rationalize their decision to increase interest rates, avoiding the need for a discourse on regime change.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In doing so, they recognized the complex trade-offs inherent in balancing various macroeconomic objectives and the challenging decisions they had to face.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] It was with this new monetary strategy that the eurozone found itself facing rising inflation in 2021.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Recent studies stated that key debate among policymakers centered on whether this inflationary trend would be transitory or permanent.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Paul Krugman argued that the current inflationary surge would prove to be transitory, whereas other economists such as Olivier Blanchard and Larry Summers had issued warnings regarding the possible persistence of this inflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Initially, both the European Central Bank and the Federal Reserve misjudged the situation, assuming the inflation spike to be temporary and expecting a swift return to their inflation target.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This misperception led to the ECB's initial inaction regarding its monetary policy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This decision came in late July 2022 for the ECB, when the inflation rate in the eurozone was already at 8.9% and had been higher than the 2% target for more than a year, and in March 2022 for the FED.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The European Central Bank's response to the Federal Reserve's actions can partly be attributed to concerns about imported inflation from the USA.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Specifically, if the FED increases its policy rates while the ECB remains static, it could lead to a depreciation of the euro against the dollar.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Such a scenario would likely result in higher import costs for the eurozone, as many global trade goods are priced in dollars.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On the other hand, this would benefit the US economy by making imports from the eurozone cheaper.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Furthermore, the impact of US dollar appreciation, following the FED's policy rate hikes, tends to be more pronounced in the international inflation rates of energy and food.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These commodities are commonly priced in US dollars, making their inflation rates more sensitive to exchange rate variations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In the European Union, public inflation expectations are significantly influenced by the prices of energy and food.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Thus, this form of imported inflation can further exacerbate overall inflation levels of the eurozone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB also declared its intention to systematically diminish net asset purchases within their asset purchase program (APP) and end them under the pandemic emergency purchase program (PEPP) launched during the COVID crisis by the first trimester of 2022.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On the other hand, the Federal Reserve initiated the reduction of its asset purchase program in November 2021, to finally stop it by March 2022.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The Asset Purchase Programs of the ECB initially boosted asset values on bank balance sheets and led to expectations of lower future short short-term interest rates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These programs also raised inflation expectations, eventually reanchoring long-term inflation expectations.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Phasing out the Asset Purchase Programs thus signals alignment with the different policy rate hikes in an attempt to cool down the economy and demonstrates a commitment to combating inflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Research indicates that the European Central Bank responded to the escalating inflation more slowly and cautiously than the FED, showing hopes that a moderate tightening of monetary policy would suffice.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The ECB was notably slower in acknowledging the mistaken nature of its initial assumption that the inflationary trend would be transitory.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The transition away from extremely low interest rates was soon accompanied by various rate increases, culminating in the ECB's main rate reaching 4% by the end of September.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In contrast, the FED's latest rate hike elevated the Effective Federal Funds Rate to 5.33% in August, underscoring a more aggressive and rapid tightening of monetary policy compared to the ECB's approach.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the global monetary tightening cycle turned out to be the most synchronized one in the past half-century.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] By February 2023, more than 90% of economies had hiked their policy rates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The latest peak of highly synchronized action by central banks was during the 1970s and the oil prices shocks where 70% of them had raised their interest rates.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Criticism first emerged regarding the methodologies used for inflation estimation and their failure to anticipate the inflation surge.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] A primary critique focused on the inadequacy of traditional tools like the Phillips Curve, which examines the relationship between inflation and certain economic activity indicators, for accurately forecasting inflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] During the 1970s, the Phillips Curve also faced significant criticism for its inability to accurately predict the inflation experienced in that decade.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This period marked a critical reassessment of the curve's predictive capacity, particularly in the context of the economic phenomena of the time.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Traditional indicators used for forecasting economic dynamics, such as the output and unemployment gaps, were found to be inadequate in signaling the overheating of the economy and the prevailing tight labor market conditions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Moreover, the important belief among central banks that sustained inflationary increases are a consequence of unanchored long-term inflation expectations was challenged during 2021–2022.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] During this period, inflation expectations remained relatively stable, leading to the misinterpretations by the European Central Bank and other monetary authorities regarding the inflationary trend's nature.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Both the FED and the ECB argued that the rise in inflation was only temporary and was the sole result of post-pandemic supply disruptions on a few selected goods and services (food and energy).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The FED and the ECB then maintained their expansionary monetary policy, keeping interest rates low.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Some critics have also emerged saying that it was complicated for independent central banks, including the ECB, to accurately assess during a synchronized policy rate hike the potential spillovers of cross-countries monetary policy on the inflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This might lead to excessive monetary tightening (higher interest rates) in unusual circumstances.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Concerns have also been raised about the European Central Bank's effectiveness in addressing the recent surge in energy prices.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Some experts suggest that the eurozone should be viewed as a small open economy, implying that changes in its demand may not significantly impact global prices.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Moreover, they argue that monetary policy might have minimal influence on the global demand for energy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This is because household demand for essentials like heating and transportation is believed to be relatively insensitive to price changes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Additionally, while a stronger euro could theoretically lead to lower import prices, it's uncertain whether these savings would be effectively passed on to consumers.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, recent studies contradict these views by highlighting the significant role of energy prices in the transmission of monetary policy within the eurozone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] An increase in the ECB's policy rates tends to appreciate the euro against the dollar.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This appreciation can lead to higher local energy costs but may also reduce demand, potentially lowering global energy prices.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] These studies support the ECB's decision to follow the Federal Reserve's lead in raising policy rates, which appears to have been a strategic move to curb imported inflation and address the spike in energy prices.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The implementing a of tighter monetary policy has emerged as the eurozone solution to fight the latest inflationary pressure.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, this approach bears the risk of hindering the progress of the economic revival post-COVID.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Raising interest rates is a strategic move by the ECB with specific aims: to decelerate economic activity, stabilize inflation expectations, and steer towards lower inflation levels.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Studies have shown that as interest rates rise, the price on the world market does not really change.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] However, the Euro becomes more attractive to investors, leading to its appreciation against other currencies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] This change benefits households paying for gas in Euros, as it translates into lower prices for dollar-traded oil.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] On the other hand, the increase in interest rates, while helping to suppress prices, also places strains on the manufacturing sector and the labor market.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The aftermath of this shock sees tighter financing conditions and a dip in demand, resulting in a slight uptick in unemployment rates, going beyond 0.1 percentage points.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Although the study shows that manufacturing sector quickly rebounds, returning to its pre-shock state within about three months, the impact on unemployment rates lingers for a longer period.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] In May 2025, the European Central Bank launched a platform involving around 70 market participants to test digital euro payment functionalities and use cases.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] The initiative includes banks, fintechs, and merchants, aiming to simulate a digital euro ecosystem and support the development of future payment solutions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] As of August 2025, enabling legislation has not been passed by European lawmakers to enable the digital euro to become operational.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p01] Bank president Lagarde has urged lawmakers to "seize the 'euro moment'" and rapidly put in place a legislative framework to "pave the way for the potential introduction of a digital euro," in order to address the considerable risk posed by U.S. dollar-linked stablecoins.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The ECB has one primary objective – price stability – subject to which it may pursue secondary objectives.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The primary objective of the European Central Bank, set out in Article 127(1) of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union, is to maintain price stability within the Eurozone.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] However the EU Treaties do not specify exactly how the ECB should pursue this objective.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The European Central Bank has ample discretion over the way it pursues its price stability objective, as it can self-decide on the inflation target, and may also influence the way inflation is being measured.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In May 2003, following a thorough review of the ECB's monetary policy strategy, the Governing Council clarified that "in the pursuit of price stability, it aims to maintain inflation rates below, but close to, 2% over the medium term".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In 2016, the European Central Bank's president has further adjusted its communication, by introducing the notion of "symmetry" in its definition of its target, thus making it clear that the ECB should respond both to inflationary pressures and to deflationary pressures.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] On 8 July 2021, as a result of the strategic review led by the new president Christine Lagarde, the ECB officially abandoned the "below but close to two per cent" definition and adopted instead a 2% symmetric inflation target over the medium term.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] This legal provision is often considered to provide a "secondary mandate" to the ECB and offers ample justifications for the ECB to also prioritize other considerations such as full employment or environmental protection, which are mentioned in the Article 3 of the Treaty on the European Union.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] At the same time, economists and commentators are often divided on whether and how the ECB should pursue those secondary objectives, in particular the environmental impact.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] ECB official have also frequently pointed out the possible contradictions between those secondary objectives.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] To better guide the ECB's action on its secondary objectives, it has been suggested that closer consultation with the European Parliament would be warranted.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In 2023, the ECB recognised the possible role of the European Parliament in the prioritisation of its secondary objectives.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The principal monetary policy tool of the European central bank is collateralised borrowing or repo agreements.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The collateral used by the ECB is typically high quality public and private sector debt.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] All lending to credit institutions must be collateralised as required by Article 18 of the Statute of the ESCB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The criteria for determining "high quality" for public debt have been preconditions for membership in the European Union: total debt must not be too large in relation to a gross domestic product, for example, and deficits in any given year must not become too large.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Though these criteria are fairly simple, a number of accounting techniques may hide the underlying reality of fiscal solvency—or the lack of the same.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In the United States Federal Reserve, the Federal Reserve buys assets: typically, bonds issued by the Federal government.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] There is no limit on the bonds that it can buy and one of the tools at its disposal in a financial crisis is to take such extraordinary measures as the purchase of large amounts of assets such as commercial paper.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The purpose of such operations is to ensure that adequate liquidity is available for the functioning of the financial system.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The Eurosystem, on the other hand, uses collateralized lending as a default instrument.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] There are about 1,500 eligible banks which may bid for short-term repo contracts.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The difference is that banks in effect borrow cash from the ECB and must pay it back; the short durations allow interest rates to be adjusted continually.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] When the repo notes come due the participating banks bid again.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] An increase in the number of notes offered at auction allows an increase in liquidity in the economy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The contracts are carried on the asset side of the European Central Bank's balance sheet and the resulting deposits in member banks are carried as a liability.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In layman's terms, the liability of the central bank is money, and an increase in deposits in member banks carried as a liability by the central bank, means that more money has been put into the economy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] To qualify for participation in the auctions, banks must be able to offer proof of appropriate collateral in the form of loans to other entities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] These can be the public debt of member states, but a fairly wide range of private banking securities are also accepted.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The Executive Board is responsible for the implementation of monetary policy (defined by the Governing Council) and the day-to-day running of the bank.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It can issue decisions to national central banks and may also exercise powers delegated to it by the Governing Council.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Executive Board members are assigned a portfolio of responsibilities by the President of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The executive board normally meets every Tuesday.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It is composed of the President of the Bank (currently Christine Lagarde), the Vice-President (currently Boris Vujčić) and four other members.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] They are all appointed by the European Council for non-renewable terms of eight years.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] José Manuel González-Páramo, a Spanish member of the executive board since June 2004, was due to leave the board in early June 2012, but no replacement had been named as of late May.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The Spanish had nominated Barcelona-born Antonio Sáinz de Vicuña – an ECB veteran who heads its legal department – as González-Páramo's replacement as early as January 2012, but alternatives from Luxembourg, Finland, and Slovenia were put forward and no decision made by May.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] After a long political battle and delays due to the European Parliament's protest over the lack of gender balance at the ECB, Luxembourg's Yves Mersch was appointed as González-Páramo's replacement.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In December 2020, Frank Elderson succeeded to Yves Mersch at the ECB's board.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The Governing Council is the main decision-making body of the Eurosystem.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It comprises the members of the executive board (six in total) and the governors of the National Central Banks of the euro area countries (21 as of 2026).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] According to Article 284 of the TFEU, the President of the Economic and Financial Affairs Council (ECOFIN) and a representative from the European Commission may attend the meetings as observers, but they lack voting rights.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Since January 2015, the ECB has published on its website a summary of the Governing Council deliberations ("accounts").
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] These publications came as a partial response to recurring criticism against the ECB's opacity.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] However, in contrast to other central banks, the ECB still does not disclose individual voting records of the governors seating in its council.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In December 2025, the ECB proposed a simplification of EU banking rules to simplify the European regulatory, supervisory and reporting framework.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The proposal was introduced and endorsed by the Governing Council.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The General Council is a body dealing with transitional issues of euro adoption, for example, fixing the exchange rates of currencies being replaced by the euro (continuing the tasks of the former EMI).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It will continue to exist until all EU member states adopt the euro, at which point it will be dissolved.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It is composed of the President and Vice-President together with the governors of all of the EU's national central banks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The ECB Supervisory Board meets twice a month to discuss, plan and carry out the ECB's supervisory tasks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It proposes draft decisions to the Governing Council under the non-objection procedure.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It is composed of Chair (appointed for a non-renewable term of five years), Vice-chair (chosen from among the members of the ECB's executive board) four ECB representatives and representatives of national supervisors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] If the national supervisory authority designated by a Member State is not a national central bank (NCB), the representative of the competent authority can be accompanied by a representative from their NCB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In such cases, the representatives are together considered as one member for the purposes of the voting procedure.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It also includes the Steering Committee, which supports the activities of the supervisory board and prepares the Board's meetings.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] It is composed by the chair of the supervisory board, Vice-chair of the supervisory board, one ECB representative and five representatives of national supervisors.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The five representatives of national supervisors are appointed by the supervisory board for one year based on a rotation system that ensures a fair representation of countries.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The ECB is governed by European law directly, but its set-up resembles that of a corporation in the sense that the ECB has shareholders and stock capital.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Its initial capital was supposed to be €5 billion and the initial capital allocation key was determined in 1998 on the basis of the member states' populations and GDP, but the key is adjustable.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The euro area NCBs were required to pay their respective subscriptions to the ECB's capital in full.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The NCBs of the non-participating countries have had to pay 7% of their respective subscriptions to the ECB's capital as a contribution to the operational costs of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] As a result, the ECB was endowed with an initial capital of just under €4 billion.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The capital is held by the national central banks of the member states as shareholders.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The NCBs are the sole subscribers to and holders of the capital of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Today, ECB capital is about €11 billion, which is held by the national central banks of the member states as shareholders.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The NCBs' shares in this capital are calculated using a capital key which reflects the respective member's share in the total population and gross domestic product of the EU.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The ECB adjusts the shares every five years and whenever the number of contributing NCBs changes.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The adjustment is made on the basis of data provided by the European Commission.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] All national central banks (NCBs) that own a share of the ECB capital stock as of 1 February 2020 are listed below.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Non-Euro area NCBs are required to pay up only a very small percentage of their subscribed capital, which accounts for the different magnitudes of Euro area and Non-Euro area total paid-up capital.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In addition to capital subscriptions, the NCBs of the member states participating in the euro area provided the ECB with foreign reserve assets equivalent to around €40 billion.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The contributions of each NCB is in proportion to its share in the ECB's subscribed capital, while in return each NCB is credited by the ECB with a claim in euro equivalent to its contribution.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] 15% of the contributions was made in gold, and the remaining 85% in US dollars and UK pounds sterling.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The internal working language of the ECB is English, and press conferences are held in English.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In 2022, the ECB publishes for the first time details on the nationality of its staff, revealing an over-representation of Germans and Italians along the ECB employees, including in management positions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The European Central Bank (and by extension, the Eurosystem) is often considered as the "most independent central bank in the world".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In general terms, this means that the Eurosystem tasks and policies can be discussed, designed, decided and implemented in full autonomy, without pressure or need for instructions from any external body.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The main justification for the ECB's independence is that such an institutional setup assists the maintenance of price stability.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In return to its high degree of independence and discretion, the ECB is accountable to the European Parliament (and to a lesser extent to the European Court of Auditors, the European Ombudsman and the Court of Justice of the EU (CJEU)).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Although the accountability mechanisms are not enshrined in EU law, several practices were established following a resolution of the European Parliament adopted in 1998, which were informally agreed by the ECB, and incorporated into the Parliament's rule of procedure.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In 2023, the European Parliament and the ECB made these accountability arrangements were made more formal by signing an exchange of letter.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In 2013, an interinstitutional agreement was reached between the ECB and the European Parliament in the context of the establishment of the ECB's Banking Supervision.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] This agreement sets broader powers to the European Parliament than the established practice on the monetary policy side of the ECB's activities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] For example, under the agreement, the Parliament can veto the appointment of the chair and vice-chair of the ECB's supervisory board and may approve removals if requested by the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In addition to its independence, the ECB is subject to limited transparency obligations in contrast to EU Institutions standards and other major central banks.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Indeed, as pointed out by Transparency International, "The Treaties establish transparency and openness as principles of the EU and its institutions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] They do, however, grant the ECB a partial exemption from these principles.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] 15(3) TFEU, the ECB is bound by the EU's transparency principles "only when exercising [its] administrative tasks" (the exemption – which leaves the term "administrative tasks" undefined – equally applies to the Court of Justice of the European Union and to the European Investment Bank).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The bank is based in Ostend (East End), Frankfurt am Main.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The city is the largest financial centre in the Eurozone and the bank's location in it is fixed by the Amsterdam Treaty.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The bank moved to a new purpose-built headquarters in 2014, designed by a Vienna-based architectural office, Coop Himmelbau.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The building is approximately 180 metres (591 ft) tall and is to be accompanied by other secondary buildings on a landscaped site on the site of the former wholesale market in the eastern part of Frankfurt am Main.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The main construction on a 120,000 m2 total site area began in October 2008, and it was expected that the building would become an architectural symbol for Europe.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] While it was designed to accommodate double the number of staff who operated in the former Eurotower, that building has been retained by the ECB, owing to more space being required since it took responsibility for banking supervision.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The debate on the independence of the ECB finds its origins in the preparatory stages of the construction of the EMU.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The German government agreed to go ahead if certain crucial guarantees were respected, such as a European Central Bank independent of national governments and shielded from political pressure along the lines of the German central bank.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The French government, for its part, feared that this independence would mean that politicians would no longer have any room for manoeuvre in the process.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] A compromise was then reached by establishing a regular dialogue between the ECB and the Council of Finance Ministers of the euro area, the Eurogroup.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] There is strong consensus among economists on the value of central bank independence from politics.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The rationale behind are both empirical and theoretical.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] On the theoretical side, it's believed that time inconsistency suggests the existence of political business cycles where elected officials might take advantage of policy surprises to secure reelection.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The politician up to the election will therefore be incentivized to introduce expansionary monetary policies, reducing unemployment in the short run.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] These effects will be most likely temporary.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] By contrast, in the long run, it will increase inflation, with unemployment returning to the natural rate negating the positive effect.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Furthermore, the credibility of the central bank will deteriorate, making it more difficult to answer the market.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Additionally, empirical work has been done that defined and measured central bank independence (CBI), looking at the relationship of CBI with inflation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] According to Christopher Adolph, the alleged neutrality of central bankers is only a legal façade and not an indisputable fact.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] – *Regulation of the financial system* : The delegation of this new function to the ECB was carried out with great simplicity and with the consent of European leaders, because neither the Commission nor the Member States really wanted to obtain the monitoring of financial abuses throughout the area.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In other words, in the event of a new financial crisis, the ECB would be the perfect scapegoat.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In the aftermath of the euro area crisis, several proposals for a countervailing power were put forward, to deal with criticisms of a democratic deficit.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] For the German economist German Issing (2001) the ECB as a democratic responsibility and should be more transparent.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] According to him, this transparency could bring several advantages as the improvement of efficiency and credibility by giving the public adequate information.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Others think that the ECB should have a closer relationship with the European Parliament which could play a major role in the evaluation of the democratic responsibility of the ECB.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] For Moïse Sidiropoulos, a professor in economy: "The crisis in the euro zone came as no surprise, because the euro remains an unfinished currency, a stateless currency with a fragile political legitimacy".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] French economist Thomas Piketty wrote on his blog in 2017 that it was essential to equip the eurozone with democratic institutions.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] An economic government could for example enable it to have a common budget, common taxes and borrowing and investment capacities.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Such a government would then make the euro area more democratic and transparent by avoiding the opacity of a council such as the Eurogroup.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The creation of a sub-committee within the current European Parliament was also mentioned, in the model of the Eurogroup, which is currently an under-formation of the ECOFIN Committee.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] This would require a simple amendment to the rules of procedure and would avoid a competitive situation between two separate parliamentary assemblies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] The former President of the European Commission had, moreover, stated on this subject that he had "no sympathy for the idea of a specific Eurozone Parliament".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Paul de Grauwe and Yuemei Ji criticizes the prevailing role of central bank reserves in monetary policy.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Due to past Quantitative Easing and refinancing operations (TLTROs), major central banks are currently operating in a regime of abundance of central bank reserves.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Paul De Grauwe argues that these transfers lack economic rationale.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] Several Members of the European Parliament have also criticized the ECB for unduly boosting banks' profits.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/european-central-bank-p02] In November 2025, a group of large European banks publicly voiced resistance to the ECB's plan for a digital euro, arguing that it would duplicate existing payment infrastructures and incur excessive costs.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The **Federal Ministry of the Interior** (German: *Bundesministerium des Innern*, pronounced [ˈbʊndəsminɪsˌteːʁiʊm dɛs ˈʔɪnɐn ʔʊnt fyːɐ̯ ˈhaɪmaːt] ⓘ; abbreviated **BMI**) is a cabinet-level ministry of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] Its main office is in Berlin, with a secondary seat in Bonn.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The current minister is Alexander Dobrindt.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] It is comparable to the UK Home Office or a combination of the US Department of Homeland Security and the US Department of Justice, because both manage several law enforcement agencies.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The BMI is tasked with the internal security of Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] To fulfill this responsibility it maintains, among other agencies, the two biggest federal law enforcement agencies in Germany, the Federal Police (including the GSG 9) and the Federal Criminal Police Office.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] It is also responsible for the federal domestic intelligence agency, the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The *Reichsamt des Innern* (Imperial Office of the Interior) was the Ministry of the Interior of the German Empire.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] On the proposal of the Reichskanzler Otto von Bismarck it was created on 24 December 1879 by an Imperial decree from the Reich Chancellery.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] Like the other Imperial Offices it was directly under the control of the Reichskanzler.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The seat of the office was in Berlin and it was managed by a Secretary of State, who from 1881 until 1916 also simultaneously held the office of Vice-Chancellor.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The gazette for the publication of official notices was run by the Office from 1880.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] Entitled the *Zentralblatt für das Deutsche Reich* (ZBl), it had been published by the Reich Chancellery from 1873 until 1879.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] With the Law on the Provisional Imperial Government of 11 February 1919, the Imperial Office became the *Reichsministerium des Innern (RMI)* (Ministry of the Interior) which remained the German Ministry of the Interior during the Weimar Republic and Nazi Germany.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] From 1923 until 1945, the ministry published the government gazette, which was entitled the *Reichsministerialblatt* (RMBl).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] On 1 November 1934 it was united with the Prussian Ministry of the Interior as the *Reichs- und Preußischen Ministerium des Innern* (Imperial and Prussian Ministry of the Interior).
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] In 1949, the Imperial Ministry of the Interior (effectively defunct since the end of the war in Europe in 1945) was succeeded by the present Federal Ministry, though it served as the Interior Ministry for West Germany only until German reunification in 1990.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] From 1949 to 1970, 54% of the ministry's department leaders were former Nazi Party members, their share peaking at 66% in 1961.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] Under the Fourth Merkel cabinet, which took office in February 2018, the Ministry of the Interior was merged with the building department, which had been included in the ministry of transport from 1998 to 2013, and the environment ministry from 2013 to 2018.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The ministry, headed by the former Bavarian minister-president Horst Seehofer, was then renamed to "Interior, Building and Homeland".
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The renaming was controversial as some interpreted the term *Heimat* as old-fashioned or even nationalistic.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The Ministry of the Interior is responsible for internal security and the protection of the constitutional order, for civil protection against disasters and terrorism, for displaced persons, administrative questions, and sports.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] It is host to the Standing Committee of Interior Ministers and also drafts all passport, identity card, firearms, and explosives legislation.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The ministry also houses the Joint Anti-Terrorism Center formed in 2004 which is an information-sharing and analytical forum for all German police and intelligence agencies involved in the fight against terrorism.
[src:andreas-von-schoeler/federal-ministry-of-the-interior-and-community] The minister is supported by two parliamentary state secretaries and five state secretaries who manage the ministry's various departments.
